This paper deals with distributed computing and algorithms, which are typically categorized under cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing). The paper specifically focuses on population protocols, which are a type of distributed computing model that involves interactions between agents with limited local state. This makes cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) another likely category, as population protocols are often used to model social networks. The paper also discusses the complexity of the protocols, which falls under cs.IT (Information Theory) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). Finally, the paper proposes a new algorithm for majority, which involves synchronization and leader election, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) a possible category as well.
